chrome.notes: box-sizing is not respected when the height is calculated from window.getComputedStyle().

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 23, box-sizing is not respected when the height is calculated from window.getComputedStyle().

ie.notes: box-sizing is not respected when the height is calculated from window.getComputedStyle().

webview_android.notes: box-sizing is not respected when the height is calculated from window.getComputedStyle().

chrome.notes: Before Chrome 112, a border image's absolute or percentage length width may not take precedence over a narrower border-width (bug 767352).

edge.notes: Before Edge 112, a border image's absolute or percentage length width may not take precedence over a narrower border-width (bug 767352).

samsunginternet_android.notes: path() is the only value type supported.

ie.notes: Internet Explorer does not support the global values initial and unset.
Internet Explorer 5.5 or later supports a proprietary Matrix Filter which can be used to achieve a similar effect.

webview_android.notes: Android 2.3 has a bug where input forms will "jump" when typing, if any container element has a -webkit-transform.

ie.notes: In Internet Explorer versions before 7, when both top and bottom are specified, the element position is overconstrained and the top property has precedence; the computed value of bottom is set to -top, while its specified value is ignored.

chrome.notes: A font-stretch definition must be added to the @font-face before this property will function.

firefox.notes: CSS 2.1 leaves the behavior of max-height with table undefined. Firefox supports applying max-height to table elements.

opera.notes: CSS 2.1 leaves the behavior of max-height with table undefined. Opera supports applying max-height to table elements.

safari.notes: Scroll padding is not applied for scrolls to fragment target or scrollIntoView(), see bug 179379.

chrome.notes: Shadows affect layout in this browser. For example, if you cast an outer shadow to a box with a width of 100%, then you'll see a scrollbar.

firefox.notes: Shadows affect layout in this browser. For example, if you cast an outer shadow to a box with a width of 100%, then you'll see a scrollbar.

notes: To use box-shadow in Internet Explorer 9 or later, you must set border-collapse to separate.

Since version 5.5, Internet Explorer supports Microsoft's DropShadow and Shadow Filter. You can use this proprietary extension to cast a drop shadow (though the syntax and the effect are different from CSS3)

notes: While the CSS property is parsed and accepted, it does not have any effect.
Scheduled for removal (see bug 1388910).

ie.notes: No version of Internet Explorer supports the initial value.
Don't use -ms-word-break, which is a synonym for word-break.

firefox.notes: Starting in Firefox 67, the maximum size allowed for custom cursors is 32x32 pixels due to cursors being misused by certain malicious sites.

ie.notes: In Internet Explorer 11, when cursor is applied to an element and this element is underneath an open <select> menu and the user hovers over a <select> menu item that's on top of said element, the cursor for said element will be displayed rather than the <select>'s normal cursor. See bug 817822.

firefox.notes: The scroll-margin property can cause an element's visibility to be incorrectly calculated for element.focus(). See bug 1708303.

safari.notes: Before version 14.1, scroll margin is not applied for scrolls to fragment target or scrollIntoView(), see bug 189265.

safari_ios.notes: Before version 14.5, scroll margin is not applied for scrolls to fragment target or scrollIntoView(), see bug 189265.
